<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-761-890  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 761 890.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  Oct 16 1989 n270 p46(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Hugo dealt the Carolinas a heavy blow, but their phone systems gotoff easy. (Hurricane Hugo struck Carolina coastline Sep. 22, 1989)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Killette, Kathleen; Rockwell, Mark.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Local and long-distance communications networks in the Carolinasweathered the onslaught of Hurricane Hugo in Sep 1989 well,although two weeks after the storm struck callers fromout-of-state were still having difficulty getting through.andP;  Some65 percent of the power in South Carolina was still out as well.andO;Communications carriers in the Carolinas have not yet calculatedall the damages sustained in the storm.andP;  Southern Bell expects tobe cleaning up for the remainder of 1989.andP;  Downed cables andtelephone poles, damaged lines, electrical hazards and centralswitching offices running on emergency power were some of theproblems the company faced in the storm's aftermath.andP;  ATandamp;T hadsome success in helping customers prepare for the storm and did asmuch as it could in advance for its own network as well.andP;  MCIsuffered no major damage and offered victims of the storm freelong distance service.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Southern Bell Telephone and Telegraph Co. (services)American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (services)MCI Communications Corp. (charitable contributions).andO;Ticker:    T; MCIC.andO;Topic:     Hurricane HugoNatural DisastersDisaster RecoveryCommunications EquipmentCommunications Service Suppliers.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>